s_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dog", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.5711392164230347, "span": {"begin": 637, "end": 640}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2138"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eya1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9884724020957947, "span": {"begin": 676, "end": 680}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2138"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Eya1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955328702926636, "span": {"begin": 746, "end": 750}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hair cell lineage", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.813076913356781, "span": {"begin": 797, "end": 814}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neuronal lineage", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8367944955825806, "span": {"begin": 862, "end": 878}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2138"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eya1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991436779499054, "span": {"begin": 917, "end": 921}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Drosophila", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9821552634239197, "span": {"begin": 956, "end": 966}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eye progenitor cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8448989391326904, "span": {"begin": 972, "end": 992}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prospective crista cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7773056030273438, "span": {"begin": 1153, "end": 1177}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000165"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Acridine orange", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9854966402053833, "span": {"begin": 1199, "end": 1214}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9615"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dog", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9400701522827148, "span": {"begin": 1227, "end": 1230}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9615"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dog", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9536786675453186, "span": {"begin": 1474, "end": 1477}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "crista-specific genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6712725162506104, "span": {"begin": 1564, "end": 1585}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9615"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dog", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9193537831306458, "span": {"begin": 1619, "end": 1622}}], "text": "Zebrafish Eya1 has a role in regulating apoptosis within developing otic vesicle. In mammals Eya1 dephosphorylates histone variant H2AX and thereby affects DNA repair and cell survival (Cook et al., 2009).    Increased levels of apoptosis occur in the migrating primordia of the posterior lateral line in dog (the zebrafish mutation dog-eared that is defective in formation of the inner ear and lateral line sensory systems) embryos and as well as in regions of the developing otocyst that are mainly fated to give rise to sensory cells of the cristae.  Because of the large number of apoptotic cells observed within the otic vesicle of dog mutants, it has been proposed that eya1 could act as a suppressor of apoptosis (Kozlowski et al., 2005). Eya1 could be required to prevent apoptosis in the hair cell lineage, whereas it could have opposite actions in the neuronal lineage (Bricaud et al., 2006).  With loss of eya1 function in the eye primordium of Drosophila, the eye progenitor cells die by programmed cell death early in the differentiation process (Sahly et al., 1999).  Ectopic cell death in the developing otic vesicle is not restricted to prospective crista cells in the lateral wall. Acridine orange staining of dog embryos and wild-type siblings at several times during development revealed that cell death can occur throughout the dog otic vesicle. Ectopic cell death throughout the otic vesicle is the likely cause of the smaller otic vesicles observed in dog embryos during embryogenesis (Kozlowski et al., 2005).   By 55 hpf, the expression of crista-specific genes is severely reduced or absent in dog embryos and crista sensory hair cell bundles are absent at 72 hpf, suggesting that they have failed to differentiate (Whitfield et al., 2002).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:36:52 +0000 2026"}